    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6bdc8596-1137-4a7a-ace3-069e2f2bb5fb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old male who presents to the orthopedic outpatient clinic with a chief complaint of bilateral knee pain that has been progressively worsening over the past three years. He is a heavyset man standing at 5'10\" (178 cm) and weighing 102 kg (BMI ~32.5), with a ruddy complexion and a slightly antalgic gait. He grimaces mildly when rising from the examination chair and uses the armrests for support. His knees show visible periarticular swelling, more pronounced on the right, and he reports morning stiffness lasting approximately 20–30 minutes.\n\n{patientName} works as a warehouse shift supervisor in a logistics company, a role he has held for the past 18 years. His job involves prolonged standing, frequent stair climbing, and occasional heavy lifting. He describes his pain as a deep, aching discomfort that is worst after periods of inactivity or at the end of a long shift, rating it 6–7/10 on the numeric pain scale. Going down stairs is particularly troublesome. He reports occasional crepitus and a sense of joint \"giving way\" in his right knee.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys recreational fishing on weekends and used to play recreational football in his 30s and early 40s before knee pain forced him to stop. He lives in a two-storey home with his wife and teenage son in a suburban neighborhood. He drives to work and relies heavily on his car due to limited mobility. He has significantly reduced his physical activity over the past two years, contributing to further weight gain.\n\n{patientName} describes his diet as \"not great\" — heavy on processed foods, red meat, and beer on weekends. He smokes approximately 8–10 cigarettes per day and has done so for 25 years. He drinks alcohol socially, around 10–14 units per week. He sleeps poorly, often waking due to knee discomfort, which has led to fatigue and mild irritability. His wife has encouraged him to seek more consistent medical attention, but he has tended to \"push through\" the pain until recently."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
